    "title": "The Destroyer",
    "media_type": "Text",
    "index_reference": "the destroyer",
    "language": "eng",
    "content": "<h1>THE DESTROYER</h1><ol><li><p>A divine agent sent to carry out a sentence of destruction. The destroyer killed Egypt&apos;s firstborn. This ended the plagues and freed the Hebrews from slavery (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod12:23\">Exodus 12:23</a>; compare <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb11:28\">Hebrews 11:28</a>). The apostle Paul used the term for God’s judgment on the rebellious Israelites in the wilderness (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor10:10\">1&nbsp;Corinthians 10:10</a>; compare <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num16:44-Num16:50\">Numbers 16:44–50</a>).</p></li><li><p>In plural form, “destroyers” implies a group that causes destruction, either angels or humans (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job33:22\">Job 33:22</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer22:7\">Jeremiah 22:7</a>).</p></li><li><p>More broadly, the &quot;destroyer&quot; is any agent that causes destruction (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job15:21\">Job 15:21</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer4:7\">Jeremiah 4:7</a>).</p></li><li><p>Samson was called a destroyer by the Philistine who held him captive (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg16:24\">Judges 16:24</a>).</p></li></ol>",
